=== GREEN (ps1 side) evidence for T-003 / #147 ===

--- 1. Reject-path assertions (TEST-011) ---

named-parameter invocation (direct/test calling convention):
$ pwsh -NoProfile -File plugins/sdd-domain/scripts/domain-review-precheck.ps1 -Attempt 1 -Round 4
ERROR: domain-review-precheck: round must be between 1 and 3
EXIT:1
(matches .sh original exactly -- see red-sh.log section 1)

$ pwsh -NoProfile -File plugins/sdd-domain/scripts/domain-review-precheck.ps1 -Attempt 1 -Round 1 -EditSummary hello
ERROR: domain-review-precheck: --edit-summary is valid only after round 1
EXIT:1
(matches .sh original exactly -- see red-sh.log section 1)

positional/GNU-style invocation via array splat (the exact calling
convention tests/lib/loop-driver.ps1 uses: precheckArgs = @([string]$Attempt,
[string]$Round); if ($Round -gt 1) { precheckArgs += "--edit-summary=..." };
& $scriptPath @precheckArgs):
$ (array-splat) & domain-review-precheck.ps1 1 1 "--edit-summary=round-1-edit"
ERROR: domain-review-precheck: --edit-summary is valid only after round 1
EXIT:1
(confirms -EditSummary correctly receives and strips the raw
--edit-summary=<text> token when bound positionally by array splatting. A
dedicated splat-parameter-binding probe confirmed array splatting binds
purely positionally -- unlike `pwsh -File script.ps1 <args>` direct CLI
invocation, where PowerShell's parameter binder DOES attempt to match a
leading-dash token against a parameter name first and fails with "A
parameter cannot be found that matches parameter name". Both invocation
styles were exercised; the production calling convention (array splat) is
the one that matters for self-healing below.)

